<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Cabinet Asks for More Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economic Cabinet Asks for More Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2405232394 </F>
<F P=103> PA2405232394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] Managua BARRICADA in Spanish published a 
report on 17 May 94 pp 1, 7 that says the economic cabinet on 16 
May formally asked the diplomatic representatives of donor 
countries for $180 million in additional aid for the next three 
years. Presidency Minister Antonio Lacayo said the additional 
funds would result in higher economic growth rates. In the 
meeting, the government presented to the community of donors a 
report on progress made toward the democratization and 
macroeconomic stabilization process. It highlighted the 
demobilization of the 3-80 Northern Front, the constitutional 
reform process, and the conclusion of the Enhanced Structural 
Adjustment Facility, ESAF, negotiations. Lacayo said Nicaragua 
is requesting additional resources, not in donations but in 
credit lines in the medium and long term to help the country's 
financial system. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

