<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-101 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Proposals on Canal Termed `Positive' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton Proposals on Canal Termed `Positive' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2405192594 Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 24 May 94 p 5A </F>
<F P=103> PA2405192594 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA PRENSA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Manuel Alvarez Cedeno] </F>
  [Text] Cecilia Alegre, Panamanian member of the Canal 
Commission, has described as positive the recommendations made 
by President Bill Clinton establishing a series of changes to 
the law that regulates the canal in order to permit its orderly 
transfer to Panama on 31 December 1999. Clinton sent to the 
U.S. Congress a series of recommendations on the Canal 
Commission legislation, including one on tolls. 
  Alegre said the initiatives are positive because most of 
them 
include the majority of the recommendations made by the Canal 
Commission's Board of Directors to the U.S. Administration a few 
months ago. "I would say that, in general, they are positive 
because they change the Commission to meet the needs of the 
canal traffic, making it more flexible for maritime commerce 
demands, giving the board more power to make needed changes, and 
better preparing the Commission for the transition," she added. 
  The Canal Commission is a U.S. federal agency whose board of 
directors is made up of five North Americans and four 
Panamanians. According to the 1977 Torrijos-Carter Treaties, the 
canal will be totally in Panamanian hands on 31 December 1999. 
  Alegre said the Canal Commission presented its 
recommendations to Leon Panetta, director of the U.S. Office of 
Management and Budget. The majority of Clinton's recommendations 
"agree with ours," Alegre reiterated. 
  Clinton recommended that the process to establish tolls be 
carried out by the Canal Commission, not the U.S. president. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

