<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-101 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agreements With Colombia on Immigration Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Agreements With Colombia on Immigration Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2505020994 Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in Spanish 22 
May 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PA2505020994 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Esteban Huertas G.] </F>
  [Text] Yesterday, Colombian Foreign Minister Noemi Sanin de 
Rubio stated the two nations approved an agreement to legalize 
the immigration of approximately 15,000 citizens who have not 
processed their documents during the fifth meeting of the 
Neighboring Commission between Panama and Colombia. 
  Sanin de Rubio stressed "that this agreement will be in 
effect for citizens who arrived in Colombia or Panama two years 
ago." She also noted that "in the next two months, authorities 
will clearly demarcate the boundary stones on the 
Colombian-Panamanian border," which have not been inspected for 
years. 
  The border between the two nations is 263 km long and it 
only 
has 14 boundary stones. At the meeting, it was agreed to 
increase the number of stones to improve the border area. The 
work to establish the boundaries will be conducted by a joint 
commission, but the date has not yet been set. It was learned 
that the work might take place in the summer of 1995 when the 
two governments will verify the limits. 
  The meeting between the two governments included several 
agreements in which COPA, Avianca, and SAM airlines agreed to 
several exchanges. Colombian and Panamanian hotels signed a 
similar agreement. 
  Meanwhile, the Kuna Yala and Embera-Wounaan general 
congresses criticized the Neighboring Commission meeting because 
Indian representatives were not invited to discuss the opening 
of the Darien Gap. 
  The Indian population will be affected by the construction 
of 
the Inter-American highway, the railroad, drug trafficking, 
health issues, biodiversity conservation, and the environment. 
  The Indian chiefs questioned the meeting of the governments 
of Panama and Colombia because the rulers of these nations are 
not familiar with the situation of the Darien and Kuna Yala 
region. Only the Indian population, which has lived there for 
more than 500 years, know it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

