<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-101 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Court President Reminds Gaviria of `Limits' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Court President Reminds Gaviria of `Limits' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2405155294 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2405155294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>

<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Darcy Quinn from the "24 Hours" newscast -- </F>
passages within quotation marks recorded] 
  [Text] The conflict between the Constitutionality Court and 
President Gaviria has intensified. On the evening of 23 May, the 
president of the court disclosed a letter suggesting the dangers 
of a presidential dictatorship. Darcy Quinn has this report: 
  [Quinn] Constitutional Court President Jorge Arango began 
his 
reply to President Gaviria by reminding him of certain basic 
provisions contained in the Constitution. 
  [Arango] "The Constitution recognizes the separation of 
state 
branches --namely, the legislative, executive, and judicial 
branches -- under Article 103." 
  He also told the president that he has overlooked one very 
important point: Common citizens are permitted to do anything 
that is not specifically prohibited by law, but public servants 
must limit their actions to the duties outlined by laws and 
regulations. 
  [Arango] "With due respect for his very important office, we 
must point out that the president of the Republic is not a 
common citizen and that there are limits on his ability to 
exercise power." 
  He reminded President Gaviria that the duty of the 
Constitutional Court is to decide whether rules and regulations 
are in keeping with the Constitution. 
  [Arango] "In terms of reviewing laws, for example, this 
responsibility obviously cannot be fulfilled by Congress, which 
issues them. The chief executive cannot do this either because 
this would imply a dictatorship." 
  Finally, the Constitutional Court president outlined which 
branch of state would serve to pass judgment over members of the 
court. 
  [Arango] "If we fail to fulfill our duty, the Senate of the 
Republic is there. The Constitution states that the Senate 
should act as our judge." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

