<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fifty Arrested for Attempting Clandestine Boat Trip </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fifty Arrested for Attempting Clandestine Boat Trip </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2405205694 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1600 
GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2405205694 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Some candidates for a clandestine trip were arrested 
in Petit-Goave. Fifty Haitians, who were getting ready to embark 
by boat to the Florida coast, were arrested by police. Those 
people, mostly peasants, were brought before the court over the 
weekend. 
  Members of the civilian mission went to the spot to 
investigate this matter. It should be noted that this was the 
first significant arrest of potential boat people since 
provisional President Justice Emile Jonassaint's announcemnt of 
his government's intention to suppress the departures of boat 
people. Orders were given to representatives of the Haitian 
justice system to apply the 17 November 1980 decree, punishing 
authors and accomplices of efforts to organize clandestine trips 
to foreign countries. 
  A clear upsurge in departures of Haitian boat people to the 
Florida coast was observed during the past few weeks, following 
the announcement by U.S. President Bill Clinton of a change in 
the procedure of direct repatriation of Haitian refugees. They 
must be authorized to seek political asylum in the United 
States, on some U.S. ships, or in some other countries. These 
new measures have not gone into effect yet, however. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-57824 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat101_b_94007" </HT>


