<H3> <TI>   Ramirez To Continue Seeking `Deep Changes' in FSLN </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ramirez To Continue Seeking `Deep Changes' in FSLN </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2505191994 Managua Radio Nicaragua Network in Spanish 1200 
GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2505191994 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Radio Nicaragua Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "This Morning" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Sergio Ramirez Mercado, who was removed from the 
Sandinist National Directorate during the party's special 
congress, has said he will continue the struggle for deep 
changes in the Sandinist Front [FSLN], which is now controlled 
by Daniel Ortega's orthodox faction. I will continue promoting 
ideas of change, transformation, and renewal within the FSLN, 
the former Nicaraguan vice president and chief of the FSLN bloc 
in the National Assembly said. He added: These are not battles 
one wins in only one day. He also said a crisis emerges when 
something does not complete its birth and death processes. 
  He indicated that one must struggle for something new to be 
born in Sandinism. In that constant struggle, nothing is over 
[words indistinct] the day of its victory, Ramirez said. He 
said that in the National Assembly, the conservative group that 
now controls the party has already carried out the first phase 
involving crushing those who do not think like it does. He was 
undoubtedly referring to Daniel Ortega and those who currently 
hold important key positions in the FSLN. Ramirez said they will 
now implement the second phase of the plan to control the 
legislative faction, the newspaper BARRICADA, the media 
stations, and those who do not think like the new Sandinist 
leadership that emerged from the FSLN congress. 

</TEXT>

