<H3> <TI>   Endara Requests Review of Clinton Canal Proposals </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Endara Requests Review of Clinton Canal Proposals </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2505180794 Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 
2300 GMT 23 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2505180794 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City Circuito RPC Television </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "RPC Television News" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Guillermo Endara has requested a review of 
the U.S. proposal to make changes in the law that regulates the 
operation and administration of the Panama Canal. U.S. 
President Bill Clinton sent to the U.S. Congress a number of 
suggestions for changes in the law that regulates the Panama 
Canal. The proposal includes changing the Panama Canal 
Commission into a government corporation, making the 
requirements for the composition of its Board of Directors more 
flexible, and permitting the participation of international 
advisers in board meetings. In Panama, the president is 
studying the proposal. 
  [Begin Endara recording] I am not familiar with the details 
of Bill Clinton's proposal. From what I understand, President 
Clinton's proposal stems from a senator's proposal, which was 
studied by Panamanian authorities, and, in general, we agreed 
with it. Nevertheless, I am going to ask the five [number as 
heard] Panamanian members of the Panama Canal Commission's Board 
of Directors and the Presidential Commission on Panama Canal 
Affairs to undertake a study to enable the Panamanians to 
respond to the proposal. In general, I understand it is a good 
proposal. [end recording] 
  The changes suggested by Clinton include the review of tolls 
and the strengthening of the Panama Canal Commission 
regulations. In our country, sectors such as the Interoceanic 
Region Authority [ARI] agree with these changes. 
  [Begin ARI member Carlos Mendoza recording] The goal is to 
more smoothly, expeditiously, and functionally conduct the 
transition of the U.S.-administered Canal to a Panamanian 
administration, which begins on the first day of the year 2000. 
[end recording] 
  While officials evaluate the proposal, President Endara will 
discuss this topic with U.S. Vice President Al Gore in Honduras 
on 24 May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

