<H3> <TI>   U.S., French Firms Win Sivam Project Bid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S., French Firms Win Sivam Project Bid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2605022994 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
25 May 94 p A6 </F>

<F P=103> PY2605022994 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "O ESTADO Column" by Cristiana Lobo] </F>
  [Text] On 24 May, Strategic Affairs Secretary Mario Cesar 
Flores informed President Itamar Franco of the result of an 
international bid for the implementation of Sivam, the Amazon 
Region Surveillance System. This has been the largest bid ever 
held in Brazil, with companies from 10 countries participating. 
The project costs amount to $1.1 billion and will be implemented 
over eight years. 
  The winners of the tender are a U.S. consortium led by 
Raytheon and a French consortium led by the state-owned Thomson 
and Alcatel companies. A German consortium led by Dasa was 
selected as "an alternate." The loser was a consortium formed 
by Unisys and IBM, the two largest U.S. computer companies. 

</TEXT>

