<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gore, Central American Presidents Meet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gore, Central American Presidents Meet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2505202394 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1700 
GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2505202394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seven Central American countries have just 
participated in a brief summit with U.S. Vice President Al Gore, 
in Tegucigalpa, Honduras. Costa Rica, Panama, Guatemala, El 
Salvador, Nicaragua, Belize, and Honduras, represented first by 
their foreign ministers and later by their heads of state or 
government, presented a united bloc in the meeting with Gore, 
who had previously announced he would stay for only eight hours. 
As a matter of fact, the brief dialogue that was conducted 
spearheads the summit President Bill Clinton has called for 
December in Miami, as well as the Cartagena de Indias summit in 
Colombia on 14-15 June. 
  With the Miami summit, the United States hopes to initiate a 
new era in its ties with Latin America to eliminate vestiges of 
the Cold War. It has not invited Cuba, however, using the 
pretext of a lack of democratization; or Haiti, although its 
government is recognized by the United Nations and the OAS. 
  It was reported that during the talks between Vice President 
Gore and the leaders of the region, economic and social issues 
were discussed as well as the strengthening of democratic 
institutions, the environment, the war against drugs, and issues 
related to probable economic aid from the U.S. Government. The 
main focus of the summit, however, was getting Al Gore to 
clarify the true possibilities of Central American countries' 
joining the North American Free Trade Accord. The accord, signed 
by Mexico, the United States, and Canada, is bound to become the 
most powerful commercial bloc in the world. 
  Still convalescing from the ravages of almost a decade of 
armed conflict, and short of having consolidated true peace, 
Central America has a population of 30 million people, over 30 
percent of whom live in extreme poverty because the enormous 
economic aid provided the region by the United States was mostly 
consumed by the military in fighting the guerrillas. 
  Central America hoped the Clinton government would clearly 
define its position regarding this region and explain the 
conditions under which commercial negotiations might occur in 
order to later analyze and decide on the prospects of whether to 
move as a bloc or bilaterally, but still united. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-57886 </DOCNO>
