<H3> <TI>   Telebras Saves $2 Billion Through Research </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Telebras Saves $2 Billion Through Research </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2305145094 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
20 May 94 p 7 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2305145094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Fiber optics, digital telephone exchanges, antennas 
for satellite communications ... the first world of 
telecommunications is not far off. Actually, it is located in 
Campinas, Sao Paulo, where the Telebras [Brazilian 
Telecommunications Inc.] Research and Development Center (CPqD) 
has been operating for 18 years. In partnership with 
universities and industries, the CPqD does applied research, 
which helps the Telebras System save $2 billion per year. 
  The CPqD's 1994 budget amounts to $113.3 million -- the 
highest one since its establishment. Is so much investment 
worthwhile? CPqD Managing Director Leoncio Rezende Neto answers 
affirmatively. "Our cost-benefit ratio is 2,000 percent, much 
higher than any other activity," he said. 
  Besides promoting the technological enhancement of the 
companies operating in the Telebras System, i.e. 
government-owned telephone companies, the CPqD develops products 
and transfers them to industry. Royalties [preceding word in 
English] from these transfers have already greatly exceeded $11 
million. "We study everything, but we do not produce everything 
since we also try to establish the appropriate conditions to 
absorb foreign technology. There is no xenophobia," he said. 

</TEXT>

