<H3> <TI>   Ricupero `Concerned' Over Impact of Fixed Exchange Rate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ricupero `Concerned' Over Impact of Fixed Exchange Rate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2505145094 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 
24 May 94 p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY2505145094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Claudia de Souza] </F>
  [Excerpt] On 23 May, Finance Minister Rubens Ricupero began 
to train entrepreneurs for the fixed exchange rate system that 
will follow the implementation of the real. He said he is 
concerned about the consequences the new system will have for 
exports. The minister mentioned studies on taxation 
modifications and anti-dumping laws, without giving, however, 
any concrete details. 
  At Sao Paulo State Federation of Industries in Sao Paulo, 
Ricupero said "what in the past was compensated for with an 
exchange rate adjustment, should now be compensated for with 
more efficiency and productivity, and this calls for greater 
efforts from entrepreneurs." The economic team has already 
decided to adopt a fixed exchange rate system. When addressing 
the entrepreneurs, however, the minister preferred to use the 
expression "stable exchange rate. Fixed is a strong word 
because as physics has demonstrated, there is nothing fixed in 
the world. In a stable economy, there is no reason for the 
exchange rate to be unstable." 
  Yesterday, Ricupero adopted a more categorical position on 
the economic plan: "We are betting strongly on the stability of 
the currency and the economy," he said. He refused to debate 
the inflation rate in real value units or to make any forecast 
about it: "These are hypotheses that predict failure." [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

