<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Promises Action Against Illegal Enrichment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Promises Action Against Illegal Enrichment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2105161694 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 0158 GMT 20 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2105161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 19 May (PL) -- Official actions against 
those who have enriched themselves illicitly will be taken 
seriously and calmly, with emphasis on those who improperly took 
advantage of state goods, a top leader of the Communist Party of 
Cuba [PCC] said today. 
  During a meeting with the Veterans Association, Candido 
Palmero, first secretary of the PCC in the agricultural province 
of Havana, said several cases have been uncovered. Greater 
emphasis will be placed on those who enriched themselves at the 
expense of the state. 
  Explaining the need for Decree Law 149, Palmero noted that 
the struggle against impunity has become a task of the people 
and it will not be implemented in haste. 
  Referrring to cases of illicit enrichment already uncovered, 
he cited the case of a citizen whose eight different kinds of 
transportation and a large amount of money were confiscated. 
  Decree Law 149, promulgated by the executive at the request 
of the Cuban assembly, is among the first official actions 
against the so-called money hoarders, individuals who outrage 
the citizens because of their accumulation of resources obtained 
in a questionable manner. 
  The need to adopt measures against these individuals was a 
continuous proposal during the workers' assemblies, meetings 
held in all work places in the country in the early months of 
1994. 
  Palmero noted that it is the people who have complained 
about 
those who, according to Havana's newspaper TRIBUNA, "filled 
their coffers through speculation, theft, and shady deals." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

