<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Industries Ensure Weapons Production, Repair </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Military Industries Ensure Weapons Production, Repair </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2005223194 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2243 GMT 18 May 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2005223194 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 18 May (PL) -- The Union of Military 
Industries has the capacity to ensure the production and repair 
of the light weapons required by the Cuban Armed Forces, General 
Luis Perez Rospide has stated here. 
  The ranking officer heads a complex of factories and 
workshops that has as its primary mission maintaining combat 
weapons in top condition and overseeing the profitability of the 
12 existing enterprises. 
  In 1989, the military industry began a process of 
preparation 
to also take on production necessary for the national economy 
following the disappearance of the Soviet Union with which the 
country had 85 percent of its foreign trade. 
  Replying to a question from PRENSA LATINA, Perez Rospide 
said 
the military industries have the capacity to ensure, with its 
own experts, the repairs of tanks, airplanes, rockets, and other 
equipment necessary for defense, despite the economic 
difficulties the island is facing. 
  In addition to maintaining and modernizing combat weapons, 
the factories and workshops are also guaranteeing light weapons, 
mines, and ammunition, Perez Rospide, a graduate in tank 
engineering, said. 
  Perez Rospide told reporters during a tour of three military 
enterprises, where experts, designers, and a skilled labor force 
work, that 25 percent of its output consists of products in 
great demand among civilians. 
  The production of these enterprises includes safes, 
compressors, industrial refrigerators, wagons, computers for 
medical diagnostics, other equipment useful for tourism, public 
health, and agriculture. 

</TEXT>

