<H3> <TI>   Raul Castro Visit to Havana Farms Concludes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Raul Castro Visit to Havana Farms Concludes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2705004094 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 2300 
GMT 25 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2705004094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The visit by Army General Raul Castro, minister of 
the Revolutionary Armed Forces [FAR], heading a delegation from 
the Ministry of the FAR and the Youth Labor Army [EJT] to EJT 
integral farms in Havana Province, has concluded. 
  Today's report covers diverse aspects of the efforts of this 
military division, ranging from task work, personnel, 
production, and equipment to workers' welfare and productivity. 
This EJT division, which was created seven months ago, tends 50 
percent of Havana's lands and is already attaining significant 
results. 
  Today, Raul Castro pointed out how much can be done even 
under the difficult conditions we are experiencing, through 
optimism, better use of resources, and better organization of 
the labor force. 
  [Begin recording] [Castro] Yesterday, I briefly mentioned to 
several leaders in Alquizar, several provincial agriculture 
leaders, that the EJT is the pride of the FAR and that -- within 
the framework of the law so no one can say we are threatening 
anyone -- we are not going to let speculators or the 
inefficiency of that large bureaucracy called state collection 
pilfer their work and prevent it from reaching the population. 
[end recording] 
  Agriculture Minister Alfredo Jordan states that experiences 
such as these, given their importance and reach, ought to be 
extended to state enterprises, Basic Cooperative Production 
Units [UBPC's], and cooperatives. 
  [Begin Jordan recording] I believe this experience is 
undoubtedly the most integral and complete I have seen. In the 
future, it would be good for this type of visit, including 
Raul's presence, to continue for assessment of the work of the 
UBPC, and above all, the farming cooperatives, given their 
importance. I believe there are many interesting things here 
that we can broaden, implement, and generalize in the rest of 
the production organizations, which have also accumulated a 
series of experiences we ought to analyze. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

