<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Breakdowns at Two Plants Affect Power Supply </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Breakdowns at Two Plants Affect Power Supply </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2605151294 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 0900 
GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2605151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On the morning of 25 May, technical difficulties in 
generator units at the Antonio Guiteras electric power plant in 
Matanzas and the Antonio Maceo electric power plant in Santiago 
de Cuba have resulted in a deficit of approximately 400 
megawatts in the nation's generation of electricity. Electric 
power sector officials in Matanzas announced that in the case of 
the Antonio Guiteras plant, the problem was due to tears in the 
boiler's heat-exchange surfaces. Damage assessment and repairs 
will begin at noon today. Specialists have stated that if the 
needed repairs are found to be minor, they could be done in two 
or three days of intense work, bearing in mind that the 
temperature of the boiler must drop before repair work can begin. 
  The breakdown of the 330-megawatt generating unit caused a 
deficit of 70 megawatts during the morning and afternoon; and in 
the evening, the peak demand period, the deficit was of 90 
megawatts. 
  Specialists are making great efforts -- particularly since 
the sugarcane harvest is in the final phase and in light of 
other important economic activities -- to ready a schedule of 
outages for when power is available. The outage schedule will 
also guarantee an equitable supply of water to the residential 
sector. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

