<H3> <TI>   JCE Concludes `Initial Vote Count;' Balaguer Leads </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    JCE Concludes `Initial Vote Count;' Balaguer Leads </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2605230494 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2217 GMT 26 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2605230494 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santo Domingo, 26 May (NOTIMEX) -- Today, the 
Central Electoral Board (JCE) of the Dominican Republic 
announced the conclusion of the initial vote count for the 
general elections held on 16 May, the results of which indicated 
President Joaquin Balaguer was the winner. 
  The electoral authorities, however, refrained from 
proclaiming the Reformist Social Christian Party (PRSC) 
candidate the victor because the official resolution on charges 
of irregularities filed by the opposition is still pending. The 
JCE considers the charges filed by the opposition parties to be 
"nonexistent" despite the lack of verification of eight voting 
tables, according to JCE spokesman Francisco Alvares. 
  According to the results of the JCE, Balaguer obtained 42.44 
percent of the votes, while the largest opposition party, the 
Dominican Revolutionary Party, led by Jose Francisco Pena Gomez, 
who made charges of alleged fraud, obtained 41.40 percent. 
Third place was held by the Democratic Liberation Party (PLD) 
of former President Juan Bosch, which obtained 13.8 percent. 
  The results were suspended for a period of time until the 
authorities were able to explain which of the two presidential 
candidates had committed the least amount of electoral fraud at 
the polls. 
  Even though the figures provided by the JCE gives Balaguer 
the victory, Pena Gomez said he would continue until he has 
exhausted all peaceful means to denounce the "colossal fraud" of 
which he claims to have been a victim. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

