<F P=100> Barbados </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Balaguer Meets U.S. Envoy, Agrees To Close Border </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Balaguer Meets U.S. Envoy, Agrees To Close Border </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2605231094 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1600 
GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2605231094 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The new U.S. envoy in the Haitian crisis, William 
Grey, began his mission with a visit to the Dominican Republic. 
On 25 May, William Gray met with Dominican authorities, 
including President Balaguer, regarding the possible closure of 
the border. He was accompanied by Dante Caputo. 
  We have since learned that last night, President Balaguer 
committed himself to completely closing the border with Haiti in 
order to guarantee respect for the UN embargo against the 
country. 
  The spokesman for Mr. William Gray, U.S. special envoy, 
confirmed that President Balaguer committed himself to 
completely closing the border out of respect for Resolution 917 
of the UN Security Council, following a two-hour interview with 
the head of the Dominican state. 
  Balaguer's government, which is opposed to the embargo, has 
been accused by some North American sectors of allowing the 
passage of goods, especially fuel, to Haiti. President Balaguer 
made no comment following his meeting with President Bill 
Clinton's special envoy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

