<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ramirez To Remain in Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ramirez To Remain in Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2605154294 Managua Radio Sandino in Spanish 1200 GMT 25 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2605154294 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Radio Sandino </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Sergio Ramirez Mercado, FSLN faction leader, </F>
by unidentified reporter; place and date not given; from the 
"Events" newscast -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Ramirez] I want Nicaraguans to know we are aware 
that we still have work to do and that we have a political 
position to pursue. I want to reiterate that I have listened to 
fellow Sandinists and believe that their views are logical. The 
party's common interest is above my own. We have always worked 
for the common interest. The FSLN represents social rather than 
political interests. The FSLN seeks to benefit the majority of 
Nicaraguans; stability [words indistinct] is not enough. We 
have always strived for social laws that help alleviate the 
current poverty and misery facing Nicaragua. In light of these 
goals, which are above my personal interests, I have 
reconsidered my decision. 
  [Reporter] The decisions of the FSLN bloc will always be 
subject to the Sandinist Assembly. I am referring specifically 
to the constitutional reform regarding reelections. 
  [Ramirez] Constitutional reforms were discussed by the 
Sandinist Assembly, which is the FSLN's highest consultative 
body. The Assembly approved guidelines for negotiations, and 
the Sandinist bloc has fully complied with these guidelines. We 
have worked with the other factions on the draft constitutional 
bill, thus abiding by the said guidelines. I believe this 
matter will not be reviewed again by the new Sandinist Assembly. 
  [Reporter] Then, will the FSLN be subject to the Sandinist 
Assembly? 
  [Ramirez] There is no reason for the FSLN not to be subject 
to the Assembly since it is a political party. As William [name 
as heard] said, the Sandinist Assembly is a part of the 
political whole embodied by the FSLN. 

</TEXT>

