<F P=100> Bolivia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Reports </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2605232094 </F>
<F P=103> PY2605232094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities monitored through 26 May. 
  A Social Policy Analysis Unit study shows the poverty rate 
increased 28.4 percent in all department capitals. La Paz 
registered the highest rate with 32.3 percent; Tarija, 30.4 
percent; Cochabamba, 29.3 percent; Trinidad, 29.1 percent; 
Oruro, 27.3 percent; and Santa Cruz, 27.7 percent. The lowest 
rates were registered by El Alto with 26.9 percent; Sucre, 26.8 
percent; and Cobija, 26.9 percent. (La Paz PRESENCIA in Spanish 
16 May 94 p 4) 
  Capitalization Minister Alfonso Revollo reported the World 
Bank will grant a $50 million credit to Bolivia for the 
capitalization project. (La Paz HOY in Spanish 19 May 94 
Economic Section p 21) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

