<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Wants Import Control Laws </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Wants Import Control Laws </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2605221094 Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO in Portuguese 1611 GMT 
26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2605221094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo AGENCIA ESTADO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Sao Paulo, 26 May (AE) -- Foreign Minister Celso 
Amorim and Industry Ministry officials are debating the creation 
of legislation to allow the Brazilian Government to stem big 
flows of imported products. Amorim is concerned about the 
excessive importation of some products following the opening of 
the economy. Under the new legislation, the Industry Ministry 
might establish quotas on products for which importation is 
considered excessive. During a GAZETA MERCANTIL-sponsored 
seminar entitled "The New Map of World Commerce," Amorim 
emphasized that Brazil must have appropriate instruments to 
fight commercial dumping. The minister said the U.S. Department 
of Commerce has 600 employees working in the anti-dumping area, 
while Brazil has only four or five professionals. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

