<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   GRANMA Calls Clinton 20 May Statement `Insulting,' `Cynical' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    GRANMA Calls Clinton 20 May Statement `Insulting,' `Cynical' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2605142594 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 1300 GMT 26 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2605142594 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Morning Information Review" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Today the daily GRANMA, organ of the Central 
Committee of the Communist Party of Cuba, describes the message 
delivered by U.S. President William Clinton on 20 May as 
insulting. 
  Under the title of "Pharisaism," journalist Felix Pita 
Astudillo recalls that today, 92 years after the United States 
installed a government in Cuba, it still wants to maintain 
annexationist ideas with the intention of annexing us, at any 
cost, into its new world order. 
  After pointing out the crudeness of the message's content, 
which seems more like an electoral diatribe directed at Miami 
rather than at Cuba, Pita Astudillo notes that the Cuban people 
are not interested in the freedom advocated by the United States 
because it is inhuman and falls under the every-man-for-himself 
philosophy. 
  The journalist notes that the wishes expressed by Clinton do 
not take into account the right to life, work, education, food, 
health, or housing in either Cuba or its neighboring Latin 
American countries. There is no reference whatsoever to the 
eradication of poverty, which requires well-balanced economic 
development and a better distribution of wealth, and it simply 
deals with age-old and worn-out references to individual civil 
liberties with a vague mention of the state of law. 
  Pita Astudillo describes as cynical the argument in defense 
of the blockade, which is aimed at making it impossible for the 
Cuban people to attain prosperity and satisfy their basic needs 
as well as making us surrender through hunger. 
  The GRANMA article notes that, in his message, President 
Clinton claims Cuba and the United States have a long history of 
cooperation and admiration. Pita Astudillo concedes that 
although this history is indeed long, it is filled with 
voraciousness and disdain toward the immoral dwarfs -- the term 
the North Americans used to describe Cubans in the last century. 
  Finally, the journalist refers to the nerve it took to refer 
to Jose Marti as someone whose ideas are consistent with 
Clinton's policy, when it was precisely Marti who 105 years ago 
wrote: Cuba has never been seen by the United States as anything 
other than an savory possession whose only nuisance is its 
people, whom they view as impetuous, lazy, and loathsome. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-57992 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat103_b_94001" </HT>


