<F P=100> Barbados </F>
<H3> <TI>   Opposition Threatens To Oppose Pay Cut Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition Threatens To Oppose Pay Cut Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2705013294 Castries HTS Caribvision Television in English 
1945 GMT 26 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2705013294 </F>
<F P=104>  Castries HTS Caribvision Television </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Barbados Labor Party says it does not intend to 
take the proposed 8 percent pay cut issue lightly. Opposition 
leader (Owen Arthur) said the laws that allow government to 
interfere with the salaries of public workers as it sees fit are 
bad and offensive. According to the opposition, these laws 
should be removed from the statute books. Mr. (Arthur) says he 
is getting legal advice on the matter, which he intends to put 
before parliament. 
  [Begin (Arthur) recording] Clause 26, which was (read) as a 
basis upon which the government has acted in this instance, was 
recommended as one of those aspects of the Constitution that 
should have been changed. I deeply regret the (?Balisur) Party 
government did not change it then. I deeply regret this was not 
tested for fear... [pauses] only because we fear that because 
the government then did not have a two-thirds majority, or 
because we did not have... [pauses] [words indistinct] it was 
not changed, but it is such an offensive law that it ought to be 
off the statute books of this country. 

</TEXT>

