<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Menem: Not `Much Hurry' for U.S.-Wanted Patents Law </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Menem: Not `Much Hurry' for U.S.-Wanted Patents Law </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2705004894 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
0015 GMT 27 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY2705004894 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 26 May (NA) -- Today, President 
Carlos Menem stated "there is not all that much hurry" to debate 
the pharmaceutical patents law, and he flatly rejected the 
possibility that this would provoke "any type of friction" with 
the U.S. Government, which is demanding quick approval of the 
law. 
  "I have spoken with the ambassador (from the United States 
in 
our country, James Cheek) and he told me there is not that much 
hurry on this topic," Menem said. 
  He also highlighted the fact that "the United States 
understands that the delay in Congress is due to the need to 
achieve a better law." 
  In remarks to the Buenos Aires radio station La 9.90, the 
president again denied that the United States was applying 
pressure to get the pharmaceutical patents law approved. 

</TEXT>

