<F P=100> Libya </F>
<H3> <TI>   JANA Editor on U.S. Freezing of Iraqi Assets </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    JANA Editor on U.S. Freezing of Iraqi Assets </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105142394 Tripoli Great Jamahiriyah Radio Network in 
Arabic 1230 GMT 1 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0105142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli Great Jamahiriyah Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The U.S. House of Representatives has decided to 
seize the Iraqi assets which have been frozen in the United 
States since the Gulf war, valued at $1.2 billion. The JANA 
economic affairs editor commented on this, saying: 
  The decision of the U.S. House of Representatives to seize 
Iraqi assets deposited in American banks was a clear and direct 
robbery which is punishable by the international law that 
organizes relations between states. It is also considered as an 
open violation and blatant aggression against all financial and 
banking organizations in which dealing between states is 
achieved and also under the protection and encouragement of 
which, many states that produce raw materials have deposited 
their funds in American and European banks. 
  This measure gives a negative and even a very dangerous sign 
to Arab states that deposit funds and about the fate of the Arab 
people in the West's banks. Under the pretext of investing funds 
or protecting them from wastage and robbery, this measure 
confirms with irrefutable proof that the Arab funds in Western 
private and governmental banks are not immune, protected, or 
invested and there is no interest in their existence. 
  The measure which must be taken immediately and without 
official endorsement [as heard] is to withdraw these funds and 
bonds, and redeposit and reuse them in the Arab region, which is 
in most need of these funds in order to achieve its development, 
civilizational change, and the prosperity of its sons who are 
the ones entitled to their wealth. 

</TEXT>

