<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wrapup of Reports on Country's Political `Crisis' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wrapup of Reports on Country's Political `Crisis' </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    AFP: Danger of Further Clashes `Eased' </H4>

<F P=102> NC2904152994 Paris AFP in English 1439 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2904152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Aden, Yemen, April 29 (AFP) -- The danger of 
further bloody clashes between rival Yemeni troops eased Friday 
[29 April] after a southern armoured brigade retreated to the 
mountains around 'Imran north of Sanaa, scene of fierce tank 
battles which left more than 100 dead. 
  Military officials of the Aden-based Yemen Socialist Party 
(YSP) said the 1,200 troops pulled out after reinforcements of 
northern troops, including elite Republican Guards, arrived at 
'Imran, 60 kilometers (37 miles) north of Sanaa. 
  Yemeni journalists who visited the scene said the northern 
troops gained the upper hand in the fighting which began on 
Wednesday, and the southern forces sought refuge with an allied 
tribe, the Bakil. 
  YSP officials described the southern forces' retreat as a 
"brilliant tactical manoeuvre," which avoided unnecessary 
casualties. 
  President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih blamed south Yemeni 
"secessionists" for the fighting, which also left 200 people 
injured, and warned them to halt the provocations. 
  The official SABA' news agency said Salih, visiting northern 
troops wounded in the clashes, appealed to the southerners "to 
see reason and to adopt peaceful dialogue as a means of 
resolving differences." 
  A pro-YSP newspaper, October 14, said Friday northern troops 
based in the south were reinforcing their positions. 
  "The (northern) al-'Amaliqah brigade is stocking up with 
weapons and ammunition in order to tighten its grip on Abyan 
province and a key point commanding eastern the gateway to 
Aden," the paper said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58054 </DOCNO>
