<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wrapup of Reports on Country's Political `Crisis' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Wrapup of Reports on Country's Political `Crisis' </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Southern Troops Accused of `Escalating' Tension </H4>

<F P=102> NC2904191094 Paris AFP in English 1814 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2904191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Sanaa, April 29 (AFP) -- The authorities in 
northern Yemen Friday accused southern troops of leaving a camp 
south of Sanaa and escalating tension following fierce tank 
battles which left more than 100 dead. 
  President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih's General People's Congress 
(GPC) said a southern brigade had deployed in the Dhamar region, 
100 kilometres (60 miles) south of Sanaa, on the orders of the 
GPC's southern rival, the Aden-based Yemen Socialist Party (YSP). 
  The GPC said it feared "more widespread clashes" between 
rival northern and southern forces. 
  A military mediation committee was trying to "persuade the 
commanders of the Ba'Sahib brigade to return to their camp and 
eliminate military tension in the Dhamar region," the GPC said. 
  On April 6 the GPC accused the same brigade of shelling 
official buildings, including Republican Guard and police 
headquarters, in the Dhamar region. 
  YSP military officials said Friday a southern armoured 
brigade had retreated to the mountains around 'Imran north of 
Sanaa, following the latest fighting. 
  The officials said the 1,200 troops pulled out after 
reinforcements of northern troops, including elite Republican 
Guards, arrived at 'Imran, 60 kilometres (37 miles) north of 
Sanaa. 
  Yemeni journalists who visited the scene said the northern 
troops gained the upper hand in the fighting, and the southern 
forces sought refuge with an allied tribe, the Bakil. 
  The GPC said searches were under way for Colonel Sayf 
al-Baqri, commander of the southern armoured brigade held 
responsible for the bloody clashes in 'Imran. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

