<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   Presidential Council Statement Criticized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Presidential Council Statement Criticized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0105185994 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1810 GMT 1 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0105185994 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Aden, 1 May (MENA) -- A spokesman for the Yemeni 
Socialist Party [YSP] Political Bureau has commented on the 
Presidential Council statement that was released in Sanaa 
yesterday evening. He said that the Presidential Council has 
revealed its convictions and clarified the truth about its 
rejection of a plan to merge the armed forces that the defense 
minister put forward four times in the past few years. Merging 
the armies would have exposed the corruption and smuggling by 
the officers of the al-Ahmar clan, who rob the soldiers' 
salaries and food, torture and humiliate them, and seize funds 
earmarked for military supplies. 
  The spokesman noted that merging the armed forces would have 
meant providing them with qualified personnel who would make 
them loyal not to their tribes and clans but to the homeland and 
its constitutional institutions so the armed forces would become 
the protectors of the homeland. He pointed out that the refusal 
to merge the armed forces exposes a plan to isolate and strike 
at them, as has happened in Abyan, (Harf), Safyan, and 'Imran. 
  The spokesman criticized the Yemeni Presidential Council 
statement, which talks of democracy and legitimacy while it 
constantly tramples them. It assailed the Yemeni president and 
his method of reaching power and ruling the country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58077 </DOCNO>
